#REDIRECT [[List of São Tomé and Príncipe-related topics]]

{{DEFAULTSORT:Index of Sao Tome and Principe-related articles}}
[[Category:Indexes of topics by country|Sao Tome And Principe]]

{{short description|Two large igneous provinces in Southern Africa and Antarctica respectively}} The '''Karoo''' and '''Ferrar Large Igneous Provinces''' (LIPs) are two [[large igneous province]]s in [[Southern Africa]] and [[Antarctica]] respectively, collectively known as the '''Karoo-Ferrar''', '''Gondwana''',<ref name="Elliot-2001">E.g. {{Harvnb|Elliot|Fleming|Foland|Zhang|2001}}</ref> or '''Southeast African''' LIP,<ref>E.g. {{Harvnb|Gohl|Uenzelmann-Neben|Grobys|2011}}</ref> associated with the initial break-up of the [[Gondwana]] supercontinent at {{Circa}} {{Ma|183|{{Abbr|Ma|Million year ago}}}}. Its [[flood basalt]] mostly covers [[South Africa]] and Antarctica but portions extend further into southern Africa and into [[South America]], [[India]], [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Segev|2002|loc=Fig. 5, p. 176}}</ref>
Karoo-Ferrar formed just prior to the breakup of Gondwana in the [[Lower Jurassic]] epoch, about 183 million years ago; this timing corresponds to the [[Anoxic event#Jurassic|early Toarcian anoxic event]] and the [[Toarcian turnover|Pliensbachian-Toarcian extinction]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Jourdan|Féraud|Bertrand|Kampunzu|2005|loc=Relation with mass extinction, p. 748}}</ref> It covered about 3 x 10<sup>6</sup> km<sup>2</sup>.<ref>{{Harvnb|Jourdan|Féraud|Bertrand|Kampunzu|2005|loc=Geological setting, p. 745}}</ref> The total original volume of the flow, which extends over a distance in excess of 6000&nbsp;km (4000&nbsp;km in Antarctica alone), was in excess of 2.5 x 10<sup>6</sup> km³ (2.5 million cubic kilometres).<ref>{{Harvnb|Courtillot|Renne|2003|loc=The Karoo and Farrar provinces, p. 124}}</ref>
The Ferrar LIP is notable for long distance transport and the Karoo LIP for its large volume and chemical diversity.<ref name="Elliot-2001" />
The igneous activity of the Karoo LIP began {{Circa}} {{Ma|204|Ma}} at the northern margin of the province. The long-lasting [[Chon-Aike Province]] in Patagonia, the Antarctic Peninsula, and [[Ellsworth Land]] was activated {{Circa}} {{Ma|190|Ma}} in an unstable tectonic environment in which both extension and subduction occurred. Chon-Aike had a peak between {{Ma|183|173|Ma}} but produced continued [[magmatism]] between {{Ma|168|141|Ma}}. By {{Ma|184|175|Ma}} the Karoo magmatism had spread to Namibia, Lesotho, Lebombo, and the Ferrar province in Antarctica. The Karoo LIP ended {{Ma|145|Ma}} with peripheral eruptions in Patagonia, the Antarctica Peninsula, northern South Africa, Kerala in India, and southeast Australia. The Karoo Province uplifted southern Africa c. {{Convert|1.5|km|abbr=on}} and broke East Gondwana (India, Antarctica, and Australia) away from West Gondwana (South America and Africa) beginning in the opening of the [[Weddell Sea]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Segev|2002|loc=The first tectonomagmatic period in southern Gondwana – the Karoo province, pp. 175–176}}</ref>
In the Cretaceous, some 15 million years after the last Karoo eruption, renewed magmatism was initiated between Mary Byrd Land in Antarctica and New Zealand from where it spread along Gondwana's southern margin, from eastern Australia to the Antarctic Peninsula. Isotopic dating suggests a series of igneous events at 133-131, 124-119, and 113-107 Ma in Australia; 110-99 Ma in Mary Byrd Land; 114-109 and 82 Ma in New Zealand; and 141 and 127 Ma in the Antarctic Peninsula. This phase of magmatism resulted in extension and rift between Australia and Antarctica, Australia and [[Lord Howe Rise]], and Mary Byrd Land and New Zealand.<ref>{{Harvnb|Segev|2002|loc=The Cretaceous Marie Byrd Land – Eastern Australia province, pp. 176–178}}</ref>
==See also== * {{annotated link|Discovery Seamounts}} * {{annotated link|Karoo Supergroup}}
