[[Category:Geographic information systems]] [[Category:Geographic data and information]]

This is a '''List of places visited by Ibn Battuta''' in the years 1325-1353.

The Moroccan traveller [[Ibn Battuta]] set out from his native town of [[Tangiers]] on a pilgrimage to [[Mecca]] in June 1325, when he was 21 years old. On completing his first ''[[hajj]]'' he continued travelling, only returning to Morocco twenty four years later in 1349. In 1350, Battuta visited [[Al-Andalus]] and then between 1352-1353 he crossed the [[Sahara Desert]] to visit the [[Kingdom of Mali]] in [[West Africa]]. On his return to [[Fes]] he dictated an account of his travels to [[Ibn Juzayy]], a scribe employed by [[Abu Inan Faris]], the [[Marinid dynasty|Marinid]] ruler of Morocco.{{sfn|Dunn|2005|pp=1-4}}

Ibn Juzayy's Arabic text was translated into English by [[Hamilton Alexander Rosskeen Gibb|Hamilton Gibb]] and Charles Beckingham and published by the [[Hakluyt Society]] in four volumes between 1958 and 1994.<ref>{{harvnb|Gibb|1958|loc=Vol. 1}}; {{harvnb|Gibb|1962|loc=Vol. 2}}; {{harvnb|Gibb|1971|loc=Vol. 3}}; {{harvnb|Gibb|Beckingham|1994|loc=Vol. 4}}</ref>

==Places visited by Ibn Battuta==
Over his lifetime, Ibn Battuta travelled over 73,000 miles (117,000&nbsp;km) and visited around 40 present-day countries.{{sfn|Dunn|2005|p=3}}

In the following list the [[Romanization]] used by Gibb and Beckingham is given in parentheses. The states are modern. Within each section the towns are listed in the order that they are first mentioned in Ibn Battuta's ''[[rihla]]''. Historians such as Hamilton Gibb and [[Ross E. Dunn|Ross Dunn]] have argued that some parts of Ibn Battuta's ''rihla'' are fictional and it is extremely unlikely that he visited all the places that he claimed. The cities for which Ibn Battuta's visit is believed to be fictional are flagged as "doubtful" in the list below.

